T1  - Hedging against interest rate risk: Reconsidering volatility-adjusted immunization
AU  - Carcano, Nicola
AU  - Foresi, Silverio
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 21
IS  - 2
SP  - 127
EP  - 141
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/02/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(96)00031-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426696000313
KW  - Term structure
KW  - Portfolio management
KW  - Immunization
KW  - Volatility
AB  - It is well known that long-term interest rates display a lower volatility than short-term interest rates. The imperfect correlation between changes in long-term and short-term interest rates is also well documented. Simple immunization techniques based on duration and convexity do not take such factors into account. This paper suggests an approach which considers unequal volatility and imperfect correlation when building immunizing portfolios. Our results suggest that this approach may lead to significant improvements over both duration-based and convexity-based immunization strategies. Volatility-adjusted and correlation-adjusted immunization also outperform strategies based on factor analysis of interest rates changes.
