T1  - Evaluating the cost-efficiency of the Italian banking system: What can be learned from the joint application of parametric and non-parametric techniques
AU  - Resti, Andrea
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 21
IS  - 2
SP  - 221
EP  - 250
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/02/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(96)00036-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426696000362
KW  - Efficiency
KW  - Data envelopment analysis
KW  - Banking
KW  - Frontiers
AB  - Research on bank efficiency has developed in two separate streams: econometric studies and Data Envelopment Analysis, a linear programming technique. These two branches of literature have developed quickly, but separately; in this paper these two approaches have been tested on a common panel of 270 Italian banks, and this has suggested the following: (i) econometric and linear programming results do not differ dramatically, when based on the same data and conceptual framework; (ii) when differences arise, they can be explained by going back to the intrinsic features of the models. Moreover, some findings on Italian banks may be of interest also to the international reader: (i) efficiency scores show a high variance; (ii) the banking system is split in two, between northern and southern banks; (iii) there is a direct (rather than inverse) relationship between productive efficiency and asset quality; (iv) the efficiency of Italian banks did not increase over the period 1988–1992.
ER  - 

